The 'MS4S16_Dataset.csv' was a breast cancer data file containinng 32 rows and 5 columns with 'id' being it's unique identifier.pandas,numpy,seaborn and matplotlib was first imported for data analysis and visualization.Eploratory data analysis started with inspecting the head and tail of the data indicating that the data contained 32 rows and 5 rows. The data had 571 enteries and missing values in each column. Furthermore, 203 missing data was indicated as the total number of missing value in each column. The *,?,-,-999,999 was converted to np.nan and the missing value increased to 358 afterwards, with the removal of duplicates 293 variables was left.

Also, proceeded with the removal of all the columns that had all its variables as missing.The 'id' column was dropped, the categorical data'diagnosis' was also dropped to ensure the calculation of the median of the numerical columns. The missing values in each column was substituted with its median and I inspected to ensure there was no more missing values in the columns. calculation of the correlation of the columns was done and the highly correlated features was removed on the rows and columns. A graphical representation of the correlation was presented.The features from the correlation was used to get the actual value. Graphical representation of the 'radius mean' and 'symmetry mean' was displayed. A standardscaler transformation was then used to transform my dataset. This compute the standarfd deviation and the mean of the features and fit it to the dataset and then transdform the data based on the statistics.

The unspervised learning was done using K-means clustering,Agglomerative clustering and dBSCAN.The standardScaler was first imported and K-means clustering was iterated over a range of clusters numbers of 2 to 7. The K-means model was fitted for eacch number of clusters and calculated and the inertia value for each model stored. The line plot of the inertia using seaborn showed that there was no clear elbow point. The silhoutte plot indicated that the appropriate clusters for the analysis is two. The scatterplot of the data indicated 2 clusters, similar to the two groups of diagnosis features.The agglomerative clustering hierrachical was represented by a dendogram also showed 2 distinct clusters, which afirms that there are 2 distinct clusters. In the dBSCAN the data points was assigned a noise.

With classification, the dataset was split into training set and test set. A binary column was created named 'class' which indicated benign cancer as 0 and malignant cancer cells as 1. The shape of the training set was then determined, it contained 114 data samples and 13 features The StandardScaler was fitted to the training data (X_train) and transformed both the training and testing data using the fitted scaler which ensures that both sets are scaled using the same parameters learned from the training data, maintaining consistency between the training and testing sets.The performance of the model on the test data was then assessed. The decision tree classifier was then used to build a decison tree model that predicted the target variable by learning simple decision rules inferred from the features. After making the predictions (y_pred),metrics such as accuracy, recall, precision, and confusion matrix were used to evaluate how well the model performed. With an accurracy of 1.0, all samples in the test set are correctly classified by the model.This means there are no misclassifications, and every sample is predicted correctly.

A recall of 1.0 indicated that the classifier is correctly identifying all instances of the positive class (in this case, malignant cancer) in the test set and all malignant tumors are correctly identified and a precision of 1.0 indicated no false positives.

The confusion matrix indicated 286 true negatives (benign tumor correctly classified), 166 true positives (malignant tumor correctly classified), and no false positives or false negatives.

Overall, these evaluation metrics suggest that the Decision Tree classifier is performing very well on the test set.

In the logistic regression: Accuracy: The accuracy of approximately 0.967 indicated that around 96.7% of the samples in the test set are correctly classified by the model.

Recall: The recall of approximately 0.946 means that the classifier correctly identifies around 94.6% of the instances of the positive class (malignantcancer) in the test set. There are some malignant tumors that the model however fails to identify.

Precision: The precision of approximately 0.963 indicated that around 96.3% of the instances predicted as positive by the classifier are indeed positive. Therefore, the model has a relatively low rate of false positives.

Confusion Matrix: The confusion matrix provides a detailed breakdown of the model's performance. It shows that there are 280 true negatives (benign tumor correctly classified), 157 true positives (malignant tumor correctly classified), 6 false positives (benign tumor incorrectly classified as malignant), and 9 false negatives (malignant cancer incorrectly classified as benign).

Overall, while the model's performance is slightly below perfect, it still performs well, with high accuracy, recall, and precision. The presence of false positives and false negatives suggests areas for potential improvement.

Precision: The precision of approximately 0.964 indicated that around 96.4% of the instances predicted as positive by the classifier are indeed positive. In other words, the model has a relatively low rate of false positives.

Confusion Matrix: The confusion matrix provides a detailed breakdown of the model's performance. It shows that there are 280 true negatives (benign tumors correctly classified), 159 true positives (malignant tumors correctly classified), 6 false positives (benign tumors incorrectly classified as malignant), and 7 false negatives (malignant tumors incorrectly classified as benign).

In Conclusion,the best model for further prediction is the logistic regression based on the mean recall scores of 0.964. Recall is the appropriate score for determining malignant cancerous cells. Logistic regression scored a mean recall of 96.4% after applying cross validation on 7 datasets. This is the highest recall scores among the other algorithms.

The presence of some false positives and false negatives suggests areas for potential improvement.
